[3] Thailand
Date: 14 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Animal Disease Information news, Vol. 17, No. 20, 14 May 2004
[edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec0>
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec1>


Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza in Thailand: Follow-up report No. 14

Information received on 11 May 2004 from Dr Yukol Limlamthong, Director
General, Department of Livestock Development, Ministry of Agriculture and
Cooperatives, Bangkok:

End of previous report period: 29 Apr 2004 (see Disease Information, 17
[19], 128, dated 7 May 2004).

End of this report period: 6 May 2004.

No new outbreaks of highly pathogenic avian influenza have been found in
spite of intensive clinical surveillance.

Passive surveillance: laboratory investigations for Newcastle disease virus
and avian influenza virus were performed in all avian cases submitted for
diagnosis to the National Institute of Animal Health. During this reporting
period, there were no positive samples from 14 avian cases.

All 403 flocks sampled (samples submitted to obtain a movement permit and
ante-mortem samples) tested negative for avian influenza.

Previous Reports: See also: 7 May 2004
(<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_46.HTM#Sec3>),
30 Apr 2004, 23 Apr 2004, 9 Apr 2004, 2 Apr 2004, 26 Mar 2004, 19 Mar 2004,
12 Mar 2004, 5 Mar 2004, 27 Feb 2004, 20 Feb 2004, 13 Feb 2004, 6 Feb 2004,
23 Jan 2004

Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza in Thailand
Follow-up report No. 15

Information received on 14 May 2004 from Dr Yukol Limlamthong, Director
General, Department of Livestock Development, Ministry of Agriculture and
Cooperatives, Bangkok:

End of previous report period: 6 May 2004 (see Disease Information, 17
[20], 135, dated 14 May 2004).

End of this report period: 14 May 2004.

No new outbreaks of highly pathogenic avian influenza have been found in
spite of active clinical surveillance.

Previous Reports:
See also:
7 May 2004 (<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_46.HTM#Sec3>),
